Article: â€œThe Two Brothersâ€ Who Founded Monster Box
Genres: ['Monster Box']
Tags: ['Sunday night with Monster Box']
Creators: ['Tráº§n Tiáº¿n']
Date: 2021-03-26


Description:



Content:

These days have witnessed reporters recurrently visiting Monster Box office to interview, which reminds me of my past self. A long time ago, I, playing an interviewer, also turned up there to get some small talks with Lam and Liem for record (back then, the two "younguns'' held much of my attention). Time flies, and here I am, having worked with them in the same office for roughly one year.

There was one time I puzzled over their decision - had they quitted working to found Monster Box, to go after the so-called passions propagated in self-helps, were they never hurting for either fame or money? To earn either of which, they should have homed in other self-help. Then what is this science project for? Their answers were as follows:

â€œNah, we do long for money, woefully. So do fame. That's why I placed my best bet on such a sustainable thing as scienceâ€, replied Liem.

â€œWell if Monster Box pulls off, the outcome will be voluminous amounts of money and prominence. All legitimate. This really urged me to invest handsomely. After all, to quit a well-paid job and sell the land I inherited must be to win back a brighter future; otherwise, it would sound any less absurdâ€, added Lam.

â€œDo you see people constantly addressing the problem of cut-throat tourist prices in Vietnam? It is woefully common to earn some fast bucks, and weâ€™re seeing which in all quarters. As a rule, everyone assumes that those catchpenny tricks evidence their intelligence, along with their outstanding incomes. What theyâ€™re heedless of is that they are actually making less money than the sober-minded. The very example is YouTube. Some Youtubers are reckoning that junk videos may earn them a fortune insofar as the market. To all appearances, they all are seeing themselves as outsmarting others. Were everyone to think as superficially, that market would fall apart soon enough,â€ said Liem.

After all, to puzzle over his words is to realize that people are indeed bragging about the marketâ€™s appalment, whilst muttering on the back that "it must be a bargain, in which the early catches the worm". Seldom do they heed that they will, soon enough, run themselves into crises - easy come, easy go.

Things, however, are rarely that rosy. Before we could win back â€œfortune" and "prominence", we have to heavily invest and put in every effort beforehand. When we are yet at that doorstep, that investment has not been handsome enough, nor is that effort valiant enough. 

Everything is still going according to plan, and soon enough, we reckon, Monster Box will win back what we deserve. It is time Vietnam staged the debut of masterminds in this field. One day, should you notice Monster Box become ubiquitous after a night, the more you know that ten guys must be screaming somewhere close to you, akin to a The Social Network scene where the entire Facebook's office bursts into tears upon counting the millionth user.

But we will talk about that day later, now let us zero in the two founders who invested their every inheritance and handsomely-paid jobs on MB, who are they?

On one hand, by no means is Liem an ordinary man - never have I been less surprised by this 40-years-old. He remembers names of every Japanese idol and AKB48 member more vividly than that of customers, partners or acquaintances. Liem is also â€œwoefully sharpâ€ at face recognition. The very example of which is he perpetually propelling forward such comparisons as Ariana Grande kindred Camila Cabello (?? ğŸ˜ƒ ??).

Liem's â€‹â€‹biography, however, is indeed prominent. He did grapple with some others in a big fight (which earns him a cross-chest scar) during high-school, when he had to spend his 12th grade at a continuing education center. In the end, nonetheless, this earned him every recognition upon passing the entrance exam to Hanoi University of Science and Technology, winning a scholarship to study overseas in Korea for 2 years - given a schoolhood at a Center for Continuing Education (CCE).

Jogging his memories through these events, Liem simply commented: (1) the past fights were fiercely different from nowadaysâ€™, wherein youngsters are calling his gang to ambush others, (2) studying at the CCE was awe-inspiring, there were even monks and the elderly there. Everyone thinks that it must have been messy in there, as if it had been encapsulated with every social s-c-u-m. In fact, those sent to the center were as ordinary and naive as other younguns, yet they had no motivation to study. During exams, the entire class herded nearby to pirate mine. (3) In Korea, seldom could he learn anything given his poor English, thus, all what he did there was selling miscellaneous goods.

(To date, given he still is horrible at English, the founder has acted as a precursor to dozens of videos for foreigners).

As far as can be seen, Liem must have enjoyed his youth to the fullest, for his every surprise is yet to end. On the whole, Liem is prominent at games such as billiards, table soccer, and chess - his every prominence is at grandmaster, instead of some random pastime level. Oftentimes, he confronted every "regional grandmaster" or "the city-level table soccer champion" and ended up in either victory or tie. This man is even so extraordinary at magic that he can make his own million-view "street magic" Youtube videos, instead of some weird stuff to boast about.

After all, not only is he good at remembering acquaintances, he is also cognizant of whatever he has learned from books and daily observations. Insofar as his knowledge holds a certain degree of complexity, thus never constrained to pop-science. He even host a a small group in which we together address such problems as "Bertrand Paradox", or "how to behead Hydra".

That is a brief biography of Liem, who you had better meet in person to learn more. Remember to draw in some impressions for our founder is also somewhat absent-minded.

Accompanying him has always been Lam, the one to invest whatever he has in Monster Box, winning himself back two MB tattoos afterwards.

Lam hails from a family handsomely capable of handling interpersonal relationships, withal hypersensitive to every buried opportunity. We, all MB members, feel that his mother is akin to ours after only a few meetings. Of course those qualities have also been passed onto Lam.

Lam is also delicate to beauty, scent and orderliness. The office in which we are working was decorated by the two founders (principally Lam). Our space, thus, is always fragrant, cozy and comfortable. Let alone which, he has even engendered the serene working atmosphere at Monster Box, which every so often is spoiled by Liemâ€™s tension. Our relationships with the outsiders are also maintained thanks to him, which have earned us every milk bottle, tea, coffee, cake, ice cream, or toy that are perpetually sent to our office. Should we puzzle over this, he would reply straightforwardly enough, "I earned those". So far, no one knows from where has he â€œearnedâ€ that many things.

In general, Lam belongs to the â€œexperienced" group. He is a Millennial who loves to â€œlive to the fullestâ€ during his youth, participate in everything, travel around the globe, meet every new person and eventually settle down in Monster Box. Having been "deceived" by Liem, his contribution to Monster Box has always been pivotal to the organization.

While others home in their work, the two brothers take care of the rest so we are rarely hemmed in by any worries. The most memorable (also woefully common) moments of theirs is they two going pitching on a motorbike, looking for potential partners. Noticing that hailing taxis to the meetings were doomed to fail, they have since driven the very motorbiking having been with them since the early days. To do science with such a weak mentality sounds so wrong, I thought.

To date, the two co-founders are still on the same orientation and with a perennial enthusiasm as if they had just started this yesterday. Still, they are homing in scientific content, reminding each other that every product must bring about some values to the community, staving off every live-fast-die-young trend, holding on to the very policy of working until 3:30 pm every working day, and sticking to every promised promotion. By the same token, our office has been where everyone is lazy leaving by 3:30 and flocking to on weekends (for gaming together). Insofar as we are woefully lacking money or fame, never have hurted for fun there.

For those who are skeptical, it is true that everything is not so rosy and the two brothers are not flawless. At times we did have dissatisfactions.

For example, everyone despises Liem as a captain in football, for the founder is a bit â€˜extreme' in for-fun events as such. Roughly 100% of the company staff agreed that they located how Liem had not accompanied a player or passed the ball to others, yet blamed it on others teammates. We often prefer the team having no toxic player as such. When we play table soccer and someone except him accidentally gets lucky, Liem also gets tense as if we were deliberately "playing tricks".

Every so often, inasmuch as the two brothers had sacrificed everything for us, who then failed to accomplish some tasks, we, thus, pressured ourselves and became uneasy at which. After all, even though we often canâ€™t wait to win back some values for Monster Box, things rarely turned out "according to our wishes". By no means is it a question of "yes or no", it is rather "when". That type of question itself is pressure already.

A while ago, I saw Liem inbox the group chat saying that to meet many Monster Box fans in the conference was exhilarating. I was also elated, and indeed this is the joy we are always looking for, as a motivation, a reminder to keep us on track - to stay serious to better the community.

Excuse my borrowing some words from a previous post to end this article:

â€œGiven Monster Boxâ€™s tenet, I can be here today to brag about these stories, forasmuch as you can hear me out.

Thus, never would we give up on our very tenet.

Should we never wholeheartedly strive to bring about some values for others, can we ever sleep tight, dreaming big in which?â€






